    <title>Combined summary - UTXO growth scaling solution proposal</title>
    <updated>2023-06-12T14:45:48.838280+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2017-August/014845.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The bitcoin-dev mailing list has been discussing various proposals to address the issue of unbounded UTXO growth in Bitcoin. One proposed solution involves limiting the maximum size of the UTXO set and invalidating any UTXO not spent within a set number of blocks. The proposal also introduces a new mechanism called luster, which assigns a value to UTXOs based on their age, with those that are older losing their value over time. Another proposal suggests returning lost or stale coins to miners as a fee, rather than implementing demurrage. Additionally, there have been discussions about burning "stale" coins to encourage the use of newer, higher-security wallets, but some argue that it goes against the principles of Bitcoin. There have also been debates about implementing a system where coins expire after a certain number of years, but concerns have been raised about the inherent security risks involved in forcing individuals to bring their offline coins back online.Bitcoin developers are discussing how to limit the growth of unspent transaction outputs (UTXOs) in order to make Bitcoin sustainable and scalable. One proposed solution involves burning coins that have been inactive for a certain period of time, though some argue that this approach could cause users to lose their coins if they wait too long. Another suggestion is to require a minimum mining fee that increases based on the age of an input. A proposal was made to burn "stale" coins in order to keep mining rewards up and encourage movement of bitcoins in the economy, but concerns were raised about going against the principles of Bitcoin. The conversation also explores how advances in computer technology may make old wallets vulnerable, making it necessary for people to use newer, higher-security wallets. However, there are differing opinions on how this should be achieved, with some proposing burning or reclaiming stale coins as mining rewards, while others view this as unnecessary and irresponsible. The thread highlights the complexities and challenges of implementing features that would significantly alter the way in which Bitcoin operates.One proposed solution involves limiting the maximum size of the UTXO set, where any UTXO not spent within a set number of blocks would be considered invalid. This means miners and nodes in the Bitcoin network would only need to store that set number of blocks, capping the size of the blockchain. However, this could result in bitcoins that have not been spent for a long time being lost forever. To address this issue, a new mechanism called "luster" has been proposed, where UTXOs lose their value as they get older and are less valuable. Coins that are continuously used in the Bitcoin economy will never lose their luster, but old coins that are not circulating will start to lose it until all is lost and they become valueless.Bitcoin's scalability has been a concern for quite some time, with the UTXO (Unspent Transaction Output) set being identified as a critical issue. The UTXO set is essentially a database that keeps track of all unspent transaction outputs in the network, and its size cannot currently be safely pruned. This means that it takes up valuable space and can cause issues when it comes to scaling. Despite the concerns, the proposed solution offers a promising way forward for Bitcoin. If implemented successfully, it could help ensure the longevity of the cryptocurrency for years to come.</summary>
